    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter" xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Pieter Nanninck to Miklós Oláh (Leuven, 18 October 1536)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">1. He kept Oláh’s book for a long time because he could
                            not let it go; he hopes that Oláh wants to publish it, such work should
                            not be left in a drawer. It does not matter that there are many Erasmus
                            of Rotterdam quotes in it: what is beautiful is also beautiful second or
                            third time around. He was impressed by how well Oláh translates from
                            Greek to Latin; in his opinion, Oláh is more religious than Erasmus was.
                            He has found some things that could be corrected, but even Homer could
                            have improved his work, it is better than being criticized. 2. If he did
                            not mark anything to be corrected, Oláh would think him less of a
                            friend. Now he can admit that he also kept the book for so long because
                            he lent it to Conrad Wackers while he (Nanninck) went to visit his sick
                            mother, and then he had an eye problem after he returned. Although there
                            is no risk of blindness any more, he still cannot read much. </p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Petrus Nannius Nicolao Olao salutem plurimam. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">[1.] Nescio an debeam excusare, quod tam diu libros tuos<note
                        xml:id="note.1">It is not clear which work this is. It could be <hi
                            rend="italic">Hungaria</hi>, which according to Oláh’s comment, was
                        completed on 16 May, 1536, see <hi rend="smallcap">Eperjessy–Juhász</hi>
                        1938, V. But <hi rend="italic">Hungaria</hi> does not contain either
                        excerpts of Erasmus or Greek sentences (see below). It was probably a
                        collection of Oláh’s poems.</note> detinui, an potius, quod non diutius
                    tenui tam docte enim lucubrationes, ut nunquam lectorem satiunt, ita aegre a
                    lectore impetrant, ut e manibus deponantur, multo aegrius, ut alienentur. Certe
                    nisi mihi spes esset </p>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.3">eos aliquando in lucem exituros, nunquam commisissem, quin mihi inde
                    exemplar descripsissem. Tu autem quid facies, ignoro, ego tamen puto tales
                    lucubrationes nequaquam supprimendas. Nec deterrere te debet, quod pleraque ab
                        <persName>Erasmo</persName> translata sunt, recte enim proverbio dicitur
                        <quote xml:id="quote.1">δὶς καὶ τρὶς τὰ καλὰ.</quote><note type="quote"
                        xml:id="note.quote.1">Erasm. <hi rend="italic">Adag.</hi> 149. I,II,49. Bis
                        ac ter, quod pulchrum est.</note><note xml:id="note.2">‘what is beautiful is
                        beautiful second and third time around’.</note> Certe in usum studiosorum
                    valde fuerit, unius rei plures esse interpretationes, ita enim facilius verum
                    intellectum percipiunt, praesertim si tales sint interpretes, qui bona fide
                    Graeca reddunt, quod de te et Erasmo sanctissimo iuramento non reformidem
                    asseverare. Legi <del corresp="Olahus">et</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr"
                        >ac</add> relegi, non minori <choice>
                        <orig>diligentiam</orig>
                        <supplied>diligentia</supplied>
                    </choice>, quam voluptate tua ista scripta. Ad singulas sententias et Graeca
                    verba, et aemulum hac in re Latinum interpretem adhibui; expendi pondera,
                    dexteritates translationum, miratus sum (ita <del corresp="Olahus">ut</del><add
                        corresp="Olahus" type="insert">me</add> Deus <del corresp="Olahus">me</del>
                    bene amet) ita te esse singulorum paene verborum interpretem, ut sententiam non
                    laederes, ita sententiam reddere, ut nihil in verbis omitteretur. Propitii mihi
                    sint manes Erasmi, religiosior mihi hac in re visus es, quam ille fuit. Tamen in
                    tam felici translatione repperi, quod ut <quote xml:id="quote.2">Momus
                        arroderem, eaque subnotavi, ut Momo deesset,</quote><note type="quote"
                        xml:id="note.quote.2">Cf. Erasm. <hi rend="italic">Adag.</hi>. 474. I,V,74.
                        Momo satisfacere, et similia.</note> quod calumniari posset, nec dubito,
                    quin <del corresp="Olahus">absint</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr"
                        >adsint</add> tibi rationes, quibus tua excusare posses. Ego autem volui te
                    extra ansas (ut ita loquar) sycophantiarum esse positum; puto enim Homerum
                    potius quendam in suis mutare voluisse, quam <quote xml:id="quote.3">Zoilum
                        pati.</quote><note type="quote" xml:id="note.quote.3">Cf. Erasm. <hi
                            rend="italic">Adag.</hi> 1408. II,V,8. Zoili.</note></p>
                <p xml:id="p.4">[2.] Haec prima ratio fuit meae censurae, altera, quod verebar, ne,
                    si nihil annotassem, Gnatonem tibi aliquem non amicum habuisse arbitreris. Quare
                    iniquius quaedam vellicanda erant, quo hanc notam sive suspitionem effugerem. Id
                    quo acrius agerem et sine ulla indulgentia, persuadebam mihi opuscula tua iam
                    iam praelo committenda. Nunc autem, cur partus tuos tam diu </p>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.5">retinuerim a suo parente, causam dicam: <del corresp="Olahus"
                        >non</del> diu illi apud <persName>Goclenium</persName><note xml:id="note.3"
                        >Conrad Wackers.</note> haeserunt, antequam in meas manus pervenirent. Non
                    ita diu apud me fuerant, cum subito in patriam revocatus sum gravi aegrotatione
                    matris meae, ibi aliquot hebdomadas consumpsi, dum redeo tantopere morbum
                    oculorum, quo iam antea laborare coeperam, exagitavi, ut in grave periculum
                    caecitatis devenirem, a quo malo nondum revalui, nam, ut vides, amanuensi opera
                    ad te scribo, quod mihi tristissimum est. In rebus autem tuis alienis oculis uti
                    nolui, vel quia illis diffidebam, vel quia mihi non satisfaciebant, aegre autem
                    oculi mei tantam usuram lucis concessere, quantam in libellis tuis absumpsi.
                    Nunc periculum caecitatis abest, usus autem oculorum tam tener, ut lectionem,
                    nisi brevissimam, non sustineant. Vale, Doctissime ac Humanissime Olahe, et ut
                    alii scholas, ita tu aulam <choice>
                        <orig>erudissimis</orig>
                        <supplied>eruditissimis</supplied>
                    </choice> litteris exorna. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.6"><placeName>Lovanii</placeName> 15. Kalendas Novembris 1536.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
